      "writtenOn": "2020-11-23T15:08:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e    2) some sort of Chrome bug fix for edges I don\u0027t really understand (Florin?)\n\u003e \n\u003e I\u0027ve got no problem applying 1) any time it\u0027s legal... it\u0027s free math.  2) I don\u0027t understand enough to have an opinion on.  I would like to know if there\u0027s somewhere higher-level that logic can live... it\u0027s another why-do-this-if-Ganesh-doesn\u0027t question.\n\nIIRC it has to do with mid-point rounding: geometry (and the sprite code path) rounds a certain direction, while nearest neighbor used to round the opposite (not because it was written differently but because the sampling transform is an inverse mapping).  So e.g. nine-piece images would look all misaligned when drawn at 0.5.\n\nGanesh is consistent in this regard (presumably because it doesn\u0027t have a \"sprite\" fast path).  If you look at gm:image_scale_aligned, the GPU results do look pretty ugly (missing edges) - but that\u0027s arguably OK as long as there aren\u0027t any inconsistencies between the caps and the mid section.  IIUC GL makes no rounding guarantees other than consistency.",
      "parentUuid": "820f2bea_e4f119cd",
      "revId": "e39c7c06331562186d6a57fcb15d15681ec340cb",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
